I redo the code to use `EventServiceManager::getInstance().sendEvent()` like
```
void Subscription::sendHeartbeatEvent()
{
    // send the heartbeat message
    nlohmann::json event = messages::redfishServiceFunctional();

    std::string_view origin{};
    EventServiceManager::getInstance().sendEvent(event, origin,
                                                 "HeartbeatEvent");
}
```

On a PATCH, we could either do this, stop it / add the new always or check if heartbeat values were actually in the patch.  

Let's say you just updated retryPolicy and not HeartbeatIntervalMinutes / SendHeartbeat, this breaks the cadence..

So yeah probably something like 
```
// if Heartbeat interval or send heart were changed, cancel the heartbeat timer if running and start a new heartbeat if needed 
  if (hbIntervalMinutes || sendHeartbeat) 
{
  subValue->hbTimer.cancel();

  if (subValue->userSub->sendHeartbeat)
  {
     subValue->scheduleNextHeartbeatEvent();
  }

}
```

Could we wrap this into a method

EventServiceManager::heartbeatParametersChanged();

that way eventservicemanager owns the complete lifecycle of the timer, and hbTimer can be private.

Is this correct?  This will result in all heartbeat events having the same ID?

from the spec:

// This property shall contain a service-defined unique identifier for the event

Special emphasis on UNIQUE.  we need some mechanism to make this unique.
